The digits are stored in reverse order, and each of their nodes contains a single digit. Add the two numbers and return the sum as a linked list.
Input: l1 = [9,9,9,9,9,9,9], l2 = [9,9,9,9]
Output: [8,9,9,9,0,0,0,1]

Logic idea => 
    9999999 +
    9999
  = 89990001
  9+9 = 18 , keep 8 and put 1 on next element and keep going , here its reverse order already 


Steps:
  1. iterate using while loop till each list have null and extra quotient is 0 (for last element here its 1)
  2. add the  element from list 1 and 2 to sum.
  3. summ will have value then get split the 2 digit
      18%10 -> 8 -> keep it in current 
      18/10 -> 1 (qutioent) go for next so eep as "q"
  4.here first set the remainder value in current.next 
  5. for next iteration node , make the current.next as current example if iteration of abc , once a done need to go for c 

  
  👉 dummy node keeps the head safe
👉 current node builds the list (as pointer)
👉 current.next adds new nodes
👉 dummy.next returns actual result


Core Rule (VERY IMPORTANT)
👉 In linked list:
Node connection happens ONLY via → next
So:
current = newNode → ❌ just moves pointer
current.next = newNode → ✅ links nodes

  Its a Linked List
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * public class ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode next;
 *     ListNode() {}
 *     ListNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     ListNode(int val, ListNode next) { this.val = val; this.next = next; }
 * }
 */

 class Solution {
    public ListNode addTwoNumbers(ListNode l1, ListNode l2) {
       
        
          ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
        ListNode current = dummy;
        int q=0;
        while (null!=l1|| null!=l2 || q!=0){
            int sum = q;
             if (null!=l1) {
                      sum += l1.val;
                      l1=l1.next;
                }

            if (null!=l2) {
                 sum += l2.val;
                  l2=l2.next;
                }
            q=sum/10;
            current.next = new ListNode(sum % 10);
            current = current.next;
        }
        return dummy.next;
    }
}

